r. Peter Ludlow chronicles the faithful as they built a strong Catholic sub-state, dealing with economic uncertainty, generational outmigration, and labour unrest. As the home of the Antigonish Movement – a network of adult study clubs, cooperatives, and credit unions – the diocese became famous throughout the Catholic world.The influence of “mighty big and strong Antigonish,” as one national figure described the community, reached its zenith in the 1950s. Disciples of Antigonish traces the monumental changes that occurred within the region and the wider church over nearly a century and demonstrates that the Catholic faith in Canada went well beyond Sunday Mass.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aChina.  aChristianity.  aMystical Body.  aagriculture.  acooperatives.  acredit unions.  aculture.  adeath.  adevotion.  aeducation.  aethnicity.  afaith.  afishery.  ahealthcare.  ahistory.  aindigenous.  aindustry.  alabour.  alaity.  alanguage.  aliterature.  aoutmigration.  apriesthood.  arebellion.  astate.  asurvival.  aultramontanism.  aunrest.  awar.  awomen-religious.  awomen.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801311240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228013112423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228013112/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles